{"award_age":64.0,"bio_image":"full\/eef72b13ef9d7e0dc3ca9a4d8967b14c7c5f97db.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1886-03-08T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1972-05-04T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/thumb\/f\/fa\/Edward_Calvin_Kendall_nobel.jpg\/180px-Edward_Calvin_Kendall_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_C._Kendall","mini_bio":"<p><b>Edward Calvin Kendall<\/b> (March 8, 1886 \u2013 May 4, 1972) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemist\" title=\"Chemist\">chemist<\/a>. In 1950, Kendall was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<\/a> along with Swiss chemist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Tadeus_Reichstein\" title=\"Tadeus Reichstein\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Tadeus Reichstein<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mayo_Clinic\" title=\"Mayo Clinic\">Mayo Clinic<\/a> physician <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Philip_Showalter_Hench\" title=\"Philip Showalter Hench\">Philip S. Hench<\/a>, for their work with the hormones of the adrenal gland. Kendall did not only focus on the adrenal glands, he was also responsible for the isolation of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thyroxine\" title=\"Thyroxine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">thyroxine<\/a>, a hormone of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thyroid_gland\" title=\"Thyroid gland\" class=\"mw-redirect\">thyroid gland<\/a> and worked with the team that crystallized <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Glutathione\" title=\"Glutathione\">glutathione<\/a> and identified its chemical structure.<\/p><p>Kendall was a biochemist at the Graduate School of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mayo_Foundation\" title=\"Mayo Foundation\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Mayo Foundation<\/a> at the time of the award. He received his education at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Columbia_University\" title=\"Columbia University\">Columbia University<\/a>. After retiring from his job with the Mayo Foundation, Kendall joined the faculty at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Princeton_University\" title=\"Princeton University\">Princeton University<\/a>, where he remained until his death in 1972. Kendall Elementary School, in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norwalk,_Connecticut\" title=\"Norwalk, Connecticut\">Norwalk<\/a> is named for him.<\/p>","name":"Edward C. Kendall","place_of_birth":"South Norwalk, Connecticut ,  USA","place_of_death":null,"text":"Edward C. Kendall , Physiology or Medicine, 1950","year":1950.0}